<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="478" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,188,1403]" pageId="11" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1269,1295]" pageId="11" pageNumber="478">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Vargas &amp; Colombo" authorityYear="2020" box="[617,732,1268,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Discleroderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dolium">
<emphasis box="[617,732,1268,1294]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="478">D. dolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and they could be treated as a single species under a strictly morphological criteria. 
<collectingCountry box="[414,560,1304,1331]" name="Guam Island" pageId="11" pageNumber="478">Guam Island</collectingCountry>
, however, is an isolated island 
<quantity box="[904,1010,1304,1331]" metricMagnitude="6" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="478" unit="km" value="2500.0">2,500 km</quantity>
apart from North Ceram in 
<collectingCountry box="[1320,1432,1304,1330]" name="Indonesia" pageId="11" pageNumber="478">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
, which makes it unlikely that populations from these two interbreed. The only differences between both species are in the size of the pedicel and that the shape of the hypostomal carina being slightly more conspicuous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
